description.text:
I recently printed the awesome Stormtrooper (thingiverse.com/thing:588) and Darth Vader (thingiverse.com/thing:7215) heads and wanted to give Yoda a platform to match.
I imported Yoda along with Darth Vader into OpenSCAD and was quickly able to scale Yoda down and add a platform to suit.  Unfortunately I couldn't get OpenSCAD to render Yoda so I was a bit stuck.  After trying cloud.netfabb.com and then playing with Meshlab for ages I still couldn't get the model to render and I have no idea how to use Blender. :(
I was about to give up when I realised I could just print the platform I'd designed and then print Yoda separately on top.  It worked a treat! :)

• Download platform_for_yoda.stl.
  • Download Yoda-Lite.stl or Yoda-SuperLite.stl (I used SuperLite) from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10752.
  • Print the platform but when it finishes don't remove it from your printer and keep your heated build platform hot (if you use one).
  • Scale Yoda down by 0.75 and recenter the model. Turn off Outline in Skeinforge or you'll have to cut it away afterwards like I had to.
  • Align your print head so it is about 4mm or so above your build platform. I aimed for 4mm as that's the height of the printed platform and adjusted it by eye.
  • Print Yoda.
  • Don't profit or a certain copyright owner might come after you. ;)

description.text:
Sihedron and Sczarni Symbols made to make wax imprints on envelopes and whatnot. Makes the handouts I give as a GM more fun and immersive.
These things are to be used as molds to make clay stamps.
If you have any special requests, let me know!

Printer Brand:

Robo 3D

Printer:

R1 ABS + PLA Model

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Infill:

100

Things required Printed mold(s)
Oven-bake clay
Hobby knife/Xacto
Wax Stamp candles aka sealing wax (you might be able to use regular candles, but I've had no such luck)
Paper/Envelope/Thing to stamp
Fire source The wax is a lot cheaper on Amazon Sealing wax: http://www.amazon.com/Traditional-Postable-Sealing-Invitations-Envelope/dp/B00DQNJ9AA/ref=sr_1_8?ie=UTF8&qid=1449395199&sr=8-8&keywords=sealing+wax Oven-bake clay (sculpey): http://www.amazon.com/Sculpey-Premo-Polymer-Accents-Twinkle/dp/B00CEHFS0Y/ref=sr_1_9?s=arts-crafts&ie=UTF8&qid=1449395449&sr=1-9&keywords=sculpey+premo You can also find the wax and oven-bake clay at your local hobby store like Michaels, Hobby Lobby, Joanne's (I think) and more. The cost is significantly higher, though. Step 1 Once your print is done and cleaned up (if necessary), you will want to roll out a small ball of oven-bake clay to fit your mold. Press it onto the mold, making sure it's on there nice and good. Step 2 Flip the mold over and again, make sure the clay is completely on your mold. Then trim the excess clay around the mold. Flip and inspect - notice the clay is overhanging the mold. Trim excess. Step 3 Roll the clay trimmings, plus a little more as needed to make a handle. While the clay is still on the mold, press the handle into the clay. Make sure it attaches well! Step 4 Slowly and evenly peel back the clay from the mold. I found it easiest to go a little at a time around the mold until it started to loosen from all sides. Then it was somewhat easy to remove the whole mold. Don't worry too much if it curls a little bit as you remove it as this is fixable. Step 5 Take your removed clay and place it stamp-side down on your work surface. Now level it out to get rid of any curls that might have occurred while removing it from the mold. Wonder how it looks.... Woohoo! Perfect! Step 6 Now your casting is complete! If it looks good, it's time to bake it. Follow the directions for the clay you used. If it's not up to your expectations, don't worry! You can re-cast the clay. Just start back at step one. Step 7 Once it's done baking, let it rest for several hours to harden and set. Step 8 Time to stamp! You're going to want to moisten the stamp surface before stamping to prevent wax from sticking in any crevices. I use olive oil and it works well. Read this howto to learn how to properly stamp: http://www.artofmanliness.com/2013/02/13/wax-seals-a-history-and-how-to/ The key mold and stamp. Stamped wax! This was my first try so it's a little messy.

I created my Name Card by utilizing the tools of Illustrator.

  • Create lines around the name or any designs to detail the name card that will be rastered.
  • Make sure that the boarder of the name card is 0.001 thickness of the line, or order for the line to be a vector cut.
  • Print with the settings told and print name card.

description.text: Learn more about this and watch how I made it at https://youtu.be/Let0iM5_k1c So I'm a programmer by profession and I've had quite a few people ask if I could teach them how to code. And through doing that a few times, I've seen a few areas that people tend to struggle grasping the concept. So when I decided I wanted to make some YouTube videos about learning how to program in C#, I knew that I had to make some visual aids to help people see what's going on inside a computer at an easily understandable level. So the main part is a little container that represents a variable. Then I've got some plates with data types on them (right now I've just got string, int, double, and float). There are also connectors to clip them onto the variable. There are also numbered plates to represent index numbers in an array, and a connector to attach two variables together and chain them to make an array. So if you're interested in learning how to program, you should check out my video series on how to program in C#. It's aimed at absolute beginners. And if you're looking to teach someone else, these could help you out! All of these were printed with PLA at 0.3mm layer height with no supports. These also print fairly quickly. I think you could print the whole bunch in about an hour, depending on how much you want.

description.text: Intro

The goal of this project was to create a pocket knife that was able to be 3d printed that utilized a liner lock. Neat proof of concept, no? Knife blade is a drop point. Thumb stud is included on the blade. Cutting surface is roughly 2.7" long. The knfie can easily be opened with one hand and close with one as well. To unlock liner lock, simply push to the side with thumb, just like on a real knife with a liner lock! http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liner_lock I have printed this and it works fine. Lockup is solid. Changes in future versions include a lanyard clip as well as different blade profiles (tanto, clip point, straight back). Knife pictured is a version before this release and lacks an extra washer, and some refinement. Regardless, your knife should print fine.
Parts List

• Blade
  • Front Scale
  • Back Scale
  • Washer
  • Front Pin
  • Liner
    • Read assembly instructions for more details.
Use
Use only for discussion piece. I am not responsible for use as a weapon or any other malicious action.
Change List

v1: Initial release
v2:
  • Rear pin added, it is no longer integrated into the back scale
  • Blade now has washer built in
  • Small liner tweak

Printing
--
Print all parts at 100% infil. All parts do not require support, except the liner. Print the liner with external support and a raft!

Assembly
--
  • Place back scale on flat surface
  • Place liner lock onto back scale
  • Place blade into place on front hole
  • Place washer onto blade
  • Push front pin through front scale
  • Lay front scale on back scale, liner, blade and washer, and push both front and back pins through
  • Glue front pin to both front scale and rear scale
  • Glue back pin to front scale

description.text: UPDATE 12/5/2015 I redesigned the gear train, please print the gear files ending in "_UPDATED". The original gear train used 3:1 ration, which proved to be to high, and required too much torque to turn the handle. The new gears are a 2:1 ratio, and work great. Unfortunately to get the speed seen in my proof of concept video, the higher gear ratio would be needed. My new gear ratio works out as follows. 1:1 Bevel gears, 2:1 intermediate, 2:1 intermediate, and 18:16 final (this goofy ratio was needed to not have to redesign the case). That give a final ratio of 4.5:1. This means the final design is not as loud. The videos below show the final design in action. The video doesn't really showcase the sound very well, I believe the noise cancelling of my phone mic picking up the gear noise better than the siren noise. I assure you, while the final design is not at loud as my Proof of Concept" video, it is certainly still loud enough to grab someones attention.

This is my entry into the "Thingiversity Fall STEAM Challenge: Make It Loud!", inspired by a "police alarm" toy I once had. My design approach was centered rotor/stator design. I tried a few other designed based off of larger air sirens that have multiple tones (hi and low, creating the siren sound we are all used to) but I found that they didn't scale well. I ultimately decided to try designing the rotor with maximum air flow channels. The design worked quite well. In my "Proof of Concept" video below, I tested the rotor assembly before I designed the gear box. The assembly was chucked in a router spindle I have, and spun at about 10000 RPM. In the video, you will see I have a Db meter on an old phone of mine. The first section of the video shows a background level of about 63 Db. I then turned on the spindle without the rotor assembly attached, which was about 83 Db. I then attached the rotor assembly, which peaked at about 104 Db. The is a gain of 21 Db!!! Much better than I expected. You'll notice it only spun for a few seconds. This was due to the fact that collet for my spindle wasn't a great fit for the drive pin. With a successful rotor design I set about designing the gear box. Using a handheld tachometer, I determined I could achieve about 600 rpm with a cranking motion. This gave me a goal of designed a 16:1 ratio gear box 1(6*600=9600, close enough). My designed needed a set of right angle bevel gears. For simplicity, I kept these 1:1 ratio. The bevel gear drive and intermediate gear, at a 3:1 ratio. That drivers a second intermediate gear at 3:1. The final gear is a 2:1 ratio. The math (1:13:13:1*2:1) gave me a gear ration of 18:1. With the gear designed, all that was left was to design a case to house them, and handle to hold the whole thing. From that start I envisioned the final product to look like some kind of futuristic blaster pistol, hence the name "Wave Blaster" All design was done in Autodesk Inventor. The Design Accelerator within Inventor was used for the gear tooth design. I chose a herringbone gear pattern because they are self aligning.

Notes:
  • All parts print in the orientation seen in the thingviewer, however, I would suggest printing the Drive Pin and Crankshaft laying down, as the lateral strength will be much greater. If you do print them laying down, you will need to print at high resolution.
  • Support is needed, but is very minimal, with the exception of the Front Case and the Stator.
  • Infill can be kept low so long as you configure the number of bottom layers, top layers, and perimeters properly. For example, the back case and handle have pins that sit in sockets to hold things together, increase the perimeters until these parts become solid. Also increase the top layers, so the pins are "anchored" well.
  • Many of the moving parts where designed with little to no clearance. I did this because each printer will print tolerances differently and you want these parts to move freely with no slop. Adjust your print settings to achieve this, or use a bit sandpaper to adjust the fit.

Assembly
  • Insert DRIVE PIN into the ROTOR. The tabs on the end of the part seat in between the vertical fins of the rotor.
  • Insert the ROTOR CAP onto the ROTOR. There is a groove along the inside ring of the ROTOR this snaps into.
  • Insert STATOR into the FRONT CASE. Place the FRONT CASE on a firm surface, and push on the inner center surface of the STATOR. This part is a tight fit, but it will fit with a bit of force. NOTE: This fit will like never be able to be taken apart without damaging the STATOR.
  • Place the rotor assembly into the main assembly. The numbs on the end of the DRIVE PIN will be a tight fit, but once pushed through, the rotor assembly should spin freely. Use a bit of sandpaper if the fit is too snug.
  • Press the FINAL GEAR onto the DRIVE PIN. The smooth cylinder part should inside the hole leading to the rotor/stator assembly. The nubs on the DRIVE PIN will seat in grooves in the FINAL GEAR. Again, make sure all spins freely, sand if necessary.
  • Insert the HORN onto the front of the STATOR. Again, this snaps into a groove along.
  • Place the two INTERMEDIATE GEARs onto the standoffs in the FRONT CASE. These should fit loosely, without much play.
  • Set the BEVEL GEAR vertically in the groove of the BACK CASE. The beveled side facing the hole for the CRANKSHAFT
  • Push the CRANKSHAFT through the hole in the side of the BACK CASE. The end with the nubs should go inwards and snap into the BEVEL GEAR places int he previous step. This should again by a loose fit, with minimal play.
  • Push the CRANK HANDLE onto the CRANK SHAFT. This should be a tight fit.
  • Set the FIRST GEAR onto the tall standoff of the BACK CASE, beveled side towards the BEVEL GEAR.
  • Assemble the front and back together. This can be a bit tricky. The nubs on the two INTERMEDIATE GEARS will seat into the holes on the standoffs of the BACK CASE. There are also alignment nubs on the cases.
  • Insert the HANDLE into the two holes on the bottom of the assembly.
    • NOTE: As per the rules of the #makeitloud challenge, no glue, screws, or other fasteners are required.

this is based on the wood chopper that I found on Instructables. Made by "stevo1357" here is the link - http://www.instructables.com/id/Wood-Chopper-Windmill/

list of parts:

there are holes in the legs and body so you can pin them together, I will upload pins soon.
the arms have a 4mm hole in them, so use a M4 dome head screw to hold them in place.
the left should be tight and the right loose(so it can move).

the main crank would be best using 6 mm dia steel rod. should be faily easy to bend.

will try and design a printed part for the bit that goes around the crank, then use coat-hanger wire for the rest of it I have uploaded the drawings for the 2 cranks. description.text:
In celebration of my new Kickstarter, I put together this adorable little 'cookie' cutter that works for making homemade cat treats. I'll update this with the recipe soon. Picky Mat: cat food dish liner for when the cat dish isn't really empty (but your cat complains anyway). RECIPE
1 (5 oz) can tuna, no salt added and packed in water, drained 1 cup oat flour*(plus a couple extra tablespoons reserved for rolling out dough) 1 large egg 1 tablespoon olive oil 1 heaping tablespoon pumpkin puree *If you don’t have oat flour, just blend rolled oats in a food processer as fine as you can. 1) Preheat oven to 250 F. Line a baking sheet with parchment paper or use a Silpat. 2) In the bowl of a food processor, combine drained tuna, oat flour (or blended rolled oats), egg, olive oil and pumpkin puree. Blend until smooth. Mixture will be thick and pliable, but not terribly sticky. 3) Roll dough out to about 1/8” thick using the reserved oat flour, and cut into shapes. Alternately, for a more rustic look, roll dough into tiny balls with your hands and press down slightly with a fork. 4) Bake cookies for about 2 hours at 250 F until they become golden brown and fully dried out inside. After 2 hours, turn off the heat and let them cool in the oven. 5) Let the cookies air dry overnight, then store in an airtight container, unrefrigerated for up to one month.
